From e3122149e3ec7c2406a29b117c574892861f7a11 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: "Alejandro G. Castro" <alex@igalia.com>
Date: Fri, 22 May 2026 20:32:57 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] [GTK][WPE] Avoid main-thread geometry commits overwriting
 scrolling tree layer positions https://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=315185

Reviewed by NOBODY (OOPS!).

Follow-up to bug #315185. With the position-ownership in place, the
main thread no longer overwrites positions during a geometry commit
for the nodes which position depends on the scroll, but the compositor
can still observe a frame with a wrong position of the fixed element: both
the main thread and the scrolling thread can run applyLayerPositions walks,
each writing CoordinatedPlatformLayer::m_position one layer at a time under
that layer's m_lock. If CompositingStateOnTarget happens while main or
scrolling are doing a walk, it reads new values for the layers the
walk has already touched and old values for the rest, producing visible
jitter or step-jumps in sticky and fixed elements during heavy scroll.

We need to add an m_committedPosition snapshot on CoordinatedPlatformLayer
that the compositor reads in place of m_position. At the end of every
ScrollingTreeCoordinated::applyLayerPositionsInternal walk, visit each
Fixed, Sticky and FrameScrolling node and copy the freshly applied
m_position into m_committedPosition. Non-owned layers keep
m_committedPosition mirrored at write time so the compositor read path
stays uniform across owned and non-owned layers.

Both walks run under m_treeLock, so the apply+commit pair is atomic
relative to a competing walk on the other thread. The compositor sees
either the previous walk's snapshot or the current walk's complete
snapshot, never a mid-walk mix across layers.

